STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3">APACHE CORPORATION </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>Important Notice Regarding the Availability of Proxy
Materials </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>for the Annual Meeting of Shareholders to be held on May&nbsp;15, 2014: </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>This proxy statement, along with the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the fiscal </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013 with 2013 Summary Annual Report, are available free of </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="3"><B>charge on the Company&#146;s website at <U>http://www.apachecorp.com</U> </B></FONT></P>

stock on January&nbsp;14, 2004, to shareholders of record on December&nbsp;31, 2003, and references to the &#147;stock dividends&#148; relate to the five-percent stock dividend on Apache common stock distributed in shares of common stock on
April&nbsp;2, 2003, to shareholders of record on March&nbsp;12, 2003, and to the ten-percent stock dividend on Apache common stock distributed in shares of common stock on January&nbsp;21, 2002, to shareholders of record on December&nbsp;31, 2001.

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>APACHE CORPORATION </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>One Post Oak Central </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100 </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>Houston, Texas <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">77056-4400</FONT> </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="right">April 2, 2014 </P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>PROXY
STATEMENT </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_1"></A>GENERAL </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">This proxy statement contains information about the 2014 annual meeting of shareholders of Apache Corporation. In this proxy statement both &#147;Apache&#148;
and the &#147;Company&#148; refer to Apache Corporation. This proxy statement and the enclosed proxy card are being mailed to you by the Company&#146;s Board of Directors starting on or about April 2, 2014. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_2"></A>Purpose of the Annual Meeting </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">At the Company&#146;s annual meeting, shareholders will vote on the following matters: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Items 1- 3: election of directors; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Item&nbsp;4: ratification of appointment of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Transaction of any other business that properly comes before the meeting. As of the date of this proxy statement, the Company is not aware of any other business to come before the meeting. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">There are no rights of appraisal or similar rights of dissenters arising from matters to be acted on at the meeting. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_3"></A>Who Can Vote </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Only shareholders
of record holding shares of Apache common stock at the close of business on the record date, March&nbsp;17, 2014, are entitled to receive notice of the annual meeting and to vote the shares of Apache common stock they held on that date. The
Company&#146;s stock transfer books will not be closed. A complete list of shareholders entitled to vote at the annual meeting will be available for examination by any Apache shareholder at 2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100, Houston, Texas
77056-4400, for purposes relating to the annual meeting, during normal business hours for a period of ten days before the meeting. </P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As of February 28,
2014, there were 393,780,337 shares of Apache common stock issued and outstanding. Holders of Apache common stock are entitled to one vote per share and are not allowed to cumulate votes in the election of directors. The enclosed proxy card shows
the number of shares that you are entitled to vote. </P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_4"></A>How to Vote </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">If your shares of Apache common stock are held by a broker, bank or other nominee (in &#147;street name&#148;), you will receive instructions from them on how
to vote your shares. If your shares are held by a broker and you do not give the broker specific instructions on how to vote your shares, your broker may vote your shares at its discretion on &#147;routine&#148; matters to be acted upon at the
annual meeting. However, your shares will not be voted on any of the &#147;non-routine&#148; matters described below. An absence of voting instructions on any &#147;non-routine&#148; matters will result in a &#147;broker non-vote.&#148; </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">1 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The only &#147;routine&#148; matter to be acted upon at the annual meeting is Item&nbsp;4 &#151; ratification of
appointment of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors. All other matters to be acted upon at the annual meeting are &#147;non-routine&#148; matters and, as such, if you hold all or any portion of your shares in street
name and you do not give your broker or bank specific instructions on how to vote your shares, your shares will not be voted on any of the following &#147;non-routine&#148; matters: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

on how your shares are to be voted by: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><I></I></B>When using internet/mobile or telephone voting, the voting systems will verify that you are a shareholder through the use of a company number for
Apache and a unique control number for you. <B><I>If you vote by internet/mobile or telephone, please do not also mail the enclosed proxy card. </I></B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Whichever method you use to transmit your instructions, your shares of Apache common stock will be voted as you direct. If you sign and return the enclosed
proxy card or otherwise designate the proxies named on the proxy card to vote on your behalf, but do not specify how to vote your shares, they will be voted: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_5"></A>Voting 401(k) Savings Plan Shares </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">If you are an employee or former employee participating in the Apache 401(k) Savings Plan and have shares of Apache common stock credited to your plan account
as of the record date, such shares are shown on the enclosed proxy card, and you have the right to direct the plan trustee regarding how to vote those shares. The trustee for the 401(k) Savings Plan is Fidelity Management Trust Company. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">2 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

  <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The trustee will vote the shares in your plan account in accordance with your instructions. If you do not
send instructions (in the manner described under &#147;How to Vote&#148; above) or if your proxy card is not received by May&nbsp;11, 2014, the shares credited to your account will be voted by the trustee in the same proportion as it votes shares
for which it did receive timely instructions. </P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_6"></A>Revoking a Proxy </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">You may revoke a proxy before it is voted by submitting a new proxy with a later date (by internet, telephone or mail), by voting at the meeting, or by filing
a written revocation with Apache&#146;s corporate secretary. Your attendance at the annual meeting alone will not automatically revoke your proxy. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_7">
</A>Quorum </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The presence at the annual meeting, in person or by proxy, of the holders of a majority of the shares of Apache common stock outstanding on
the record date will constitute a quorum, permitting the business of the meeting to be conducted. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_8"></A>Votes Needed </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><I><U>Election of Directors</U></I></B><B>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</B>The affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast at the annual meeting is
required for the election of directors. You may vote FOR or AGAINST any or all director nominees or you may ABSTAIN as to one or more director nominees. As set forth in our bylaws, only votes FOR or AGAINST the election of a director nominee will be
counted. Abstentions and broker non-votes count for quorum purposes, but not for purposes of the election of directors. A vote to ABSTAIN is not treated as a vote FOR or AGAINST and thus, will have no effect on the outcome of the vote. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><I><U>Ratification of the Appointment of Independent Auditors</U></I></B>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast at
the annual meeting is required for ratification of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the Company&#146;s independent auditors. You may vote FOR or AGAINST the ratification of appointment of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the Company&#146;s independent
auditors or you may ABSTAIN. Votes cast FOR or AGAINST and ABSTENTIONS with respect to this matter will be counted as shares entitled to vote on the matter. Broker non-votes will be counted as shares entitled to vote on this matter. A vote to
ABSTAIN will have the effect of a vote AGAINST ratification of the appointment of our independent registered public accounting firm. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><I><U>Advisory
Vote to Approve the Compensation of Named Executive Officers</U></I></B>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You may vote FOR or AGAINST the advisory vote to approve the compensation of our named executive officers or you may ABSTAIN. A majority of the shares
of the Company&#146;s common stock present in person or represented by proxy at our annual meeting and entitled to vote must be voted FOR approval of the advisory proposal in order for it to pass. Votes cast FOR or AGAINST and ABSTENTIONS with
respect to the proposal will be counted as shares entitled to vote on the proposal. Broker non-votes will not be counted as shares entitled to vote on the proposal. A vote to ABSTAIN will have the effect of a vote AGAINST the proposal. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><I><U>Approval of an Amendment to our Restated Certificate of Incorporation.</U></I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Four-fifths (80%)&nbsp;of the outstanding
shares of the Company&#146;s common stock must be voted FOR the proposal to amend the Company&#146;s Restated Certificate of Incorporation to eliminate the classified Board of Directors to provide for the annual election of all directors in order
for it to pass. You may vote FOR or AGAINST the proposal, or you may ABSTAIN. Broker non-votes will be counted as shares entitled to vote on this matter. A vote to ABSTAIN or a broker non-vote will have the effect of a vote AGAINST the proposal.
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">3 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><I><U>Other Business</U>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B>The affirmative vote of a majority of the votes cast
at the annual meeting is required for approval of any other business which may properly come before the meeting or any adjournment thereof. Only votes FOR or AGAINST approval of any other business will be counted. Abstentions and broker non-votes
count for quorum purposes, but not for the voting on the approval of such other business. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_9"></A>Who Counts the Votes </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Representatives of Wells Fargo Bank, N.A. will tabulate the votes and act as inspectors of the election. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">4 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_10"></A>ELECTION OF DIRECTORS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>(ITEM NOS. 1-3 ON PROXY CARD) </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The
Company&#146;s Restated Certificate of Incorporation provides that, as near as numerically possible, one-third of the directors shall be elected at each annual meeting of shareholders. Unless directors earlier resign or are removed, their terms are
for three years, and continue thereafter until their successors are elected and qualify as directors. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The current terms of directors G. Steven Farris,
Randolph M. Ferlic, and A. D. Frazier, Jr. will expire at the annual meeting. Amy H. Nelson was appointed to the Board of Directors on February&nbsp;5, 2014. Each of Mr.&nbsp;Farris, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier, and Ms.&nbsp;Nelson has been recommended by the
Company&#146;s Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee and nominated by the Board of Directors for election by the shareholders to an additional three-year term. If elected, Mr.&nbsp;Farris, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier, and Ms.&nbsp;Nelson will serve
beginning upon their election until the annual meeting of shareholders in 2017. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Randolph M. Ferlic, who has served as a director since 1986, will retire
from the Company&#146;s Board of Directors effective as of the close of the annual meeting on May&nbsp;15, 2014. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Unless otherwise instructed, all proxies
will be voted in favor of these nominees. If one or more of the nominees is unwilling or unable to serve, the proxies will be voted only for the remaining named nominees. Proxies cannot be voted for more than three nominees. The Board of Directors
knows of no nominee for director who is unwilling or unable to serve. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS UNANIMOUSLY RECOMMENDS THAT YOU VOTE &#147;FOR&#148; THE
ELECTION OF EACH OF THE DIRECTORS. </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">5 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_11"></A>NOMINEES FOR ELECTION AS DIRECTORS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Biographical information, including principal occupation and business experience during the last five years, of each nominee for director, is set forth below.
Unless otherwise stated, the principal occupation of each nominee has been the same for the past five years. In addition, each nominee&#146;s experience, qualifications, attributes or skills to serve on our Board are discussed under the heading
&#147;Qualifications of Directors&#148; below. </P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>G. STEVEN FARRIS, </B>65, joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in 1994, was appointed
chairman of the board in January 2009, and has served as chief executive officer since May 2002. In February 2014, Mr. Farris also assumed the title of president. He served the Company as president and chief operating officer from May 1994 to
February 2009, as senior vice president from 1991 to 1994, and as vice president &#151; exploration and production from 1988 to 1991. Prior to joining Apache, Mr.&nbsp;Farris was vice president of finance and business development for Terra
Resources, Inc., a Tulsa, Oklahoma oil and gas company, from 1983 to 1988. He is a member of the Board of Visitors of M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, Houston, Texas, and is a founding member and serves on the executive committee of America&#146;s
Natural Gas Alliance (&#147;ANGA&#148;). </P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>A. D. FRAZIER, JR., </B>69, joined the Board of Directors of the Company in 1997. He has served as
president of Georgia Oak Partners, a private equity investment firm, since September 2011, having previously been a partner in Affiance, Inc., a Georgia - based bank consulting group. In July 2010, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier was appointed chairman of the
Special Council for Tax Reform and Fairness to Georgians, established by the Georgia state legislature to examine the state&#146;s tax code. He served as chairman and chief executive officer of Danka Business Systems PLC, St. Petersburg, Florida,
from March 2006 until its sale in July 2008, and was of Counsel with the law firm of Balch&nbsp;&amp; Bingham LLP, Atlanta, Georgia, from January 2005 to March 2006. From October 2004 until its sale in January 2007, he was a director and chairman of
the board of Gold Kist, Inc., Atlanta, Georgia, an integrated chicken production, processing, and marketing company. At Apache, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier is a member of the Management Development and Compensation Committee and chairman of the Stock Plan
Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>AMY H. NELSON, 44, </B>joined Apache&#146;s Board of Directors in February 2014. Ms.&nbsp;Nelson is the president of Greenridge Advisors,
LLC, an energy services and equipment consulting firm focused on the development, execution and financing of growth strategies, that she founded in 2007. Prior to Greenridge, she served as a vice president of SCF Partners, a private equity firm,
from 2000 to 2007, and she worked for Amoco Production Company in planning and engineering roles from 1992 to 1998. Since 2009, Ms.&nbsp;Nelson has been an adjunct professor of management at Rice University&#146;s Jesse H. Jones Graduate School of
Business. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">6 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_13"></A>QUALIFICATIONS OF DIRECTORS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In selecting our directors and director nominees, the CG&amp;N Committee has sought to create a Board with a broad and balanced set of skills, complemented by
diversity of experience and expertise. As is evidenced by the biographical information set forth above, each director contributes his or her own unique background which has led the CG&amp;N Committee to conclude that the Company and our shareholders
will benefit from the director&#146;s service on the Company&#146;s Board. It is equally important that the particular skill sets of each director complement the experience, qualifications, attributes and skills of our Board of Directors as a whole.
In addition to the qualifications described in the preceding biographical information, the following is a discussion of the particular experience, qualifications, attributes or skills of each director that led our Board to conclude that he or she
will contribute to the diversity of experience and expertise required for the effective functioning of our Board. </P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>G. STEVEN FARRIS</B>
Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; 31 years&#146; experience in the oil and gas industry coupled with his 19 years of direct leadership at Apache provide him with valuable insight not only into the oil and gas industry, but also the unique day-to-day operations
of Apache. Throughout his career, Mr.&nbsp;Farris has held positions of increasing responsibility in the oil and gas industry, culminating in his appointment as chief executive officer of Apache in May 2002 and chairman of the board in January 2009.
Since being named as chief operating officer in 1994, Mr.&nbsp;Farris has been instrumental in growing the Company&#146;s reserves by ten times to approximately 2.6 billion barrels of oil equivalent (&#147;boe&#148;) and production to 760,775 boe
per day. </P>  <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>A. D. FRAZIER, JR.</B> In addition to the executive positions noted in his biographical information above, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier spent a large
part of his career as an executive in the investment banking industry. He served as the chief executive officer of INVESCO, Inc., an affiliate of an independent global investment management firm, from 1997 to 2000. Mr.&nbsp;Frazier also served as
executive vice president, North American Banking Group, of First Chicago Corporation and First National Bank of Chicago from 1982 to 1991, where, among other numerous industry specialties, he oversaw the Bank&#146;s oil and gas specialty, which
provided him with an intimate knowledge of the oil and gas industry. He also served as the chief operating officer of the Atlanta Olympic Games Committee from 1991 to October 1996, and senior advisor to The Dilenschneider Group, Inc., a New
York-based public relations consulting company, during 2011. During his career, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier has been responsible for the development, management, and operation of a diverse group of businesses and organizations. Through these executive and
director positions, Mr.&nbsp;Frazier gathered extensive experience in identifying, analyzing, and managing risk across a wide range of industries. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>CHANSOO JOUNG</B> Mr.&nbsp;Joung has spent almost his entire career working in the finance industry with energy companies. He currently serves as a senior
advisor at Warburg Pincus LLC where he provides advice on new and existing investments in the energy sector. Previously, as a partner at Warburg Pincus, his duties included sourcing, executing and monitoring energy investments. Prior to joining
Warburg Pincus, Mr.&nbsp;Joung spent almost 18 years at Goldman Sachs where he worked in the Natural Resources Group and also founded and led the London-based European Energy Group in investment banking. While at Warburg Pincus, Mr.&nbsp;Joung
served on the boards of a number of private companies in a variety of sectors in the energy industry. He also served on the boards of Targa Resources Corp. and Targa Resources Partners, LP. Through his experiences in private equity and as an
investment banker, Mr.&nbsp;Joung gained significant experience with energy companies, the energy industry, and energy-related capital markets activity, which enhance his contributions to the Board. Those experiences have also given Mr.&nbsp;Joung
the ability to identify, assess, and manage risk that can affect a large energy company like Apache. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">9 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>GEORGE D. LAWRENCE</B> Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence began his oil and gas career with the predecessor to The Phoenix
Resource Companies, Inc. in 1985, holding management positions with increasing responsibility, culminating in his serving as president, chief executive officer, and a director of Phoenix from 1990 until 1996, when the company merged with Apache.
During his tenure as chief executive officer of Phoenix, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence gained valuable corporate leadership experience in all aspects of business including finance, securities, operations, strategy, and risk. At Phoenix and its predecessor,
Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence was extensively involved in international operations that were spread over several continents and he was especially instrumental in leading Phoenix&#146;s operations in Egypt, an area that remains at the core of Apache&#146;s
operations. Prior to entering the oil and gas business, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence engaged in a diversified private practice of law and also served five years at the United States Department of Justice, his last position there being the assistant chief of
the environmental enforcement section. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>JOHN E. LOWE</B> Mr.&nbsp;Lowe enjoyed a 30-year career with Phillips Petroleum Company and ConocoPhillips
serving in positions of increasing responsibilities during that time. Most recently, he served as assistant to the CEO of ConocoPhillips, a position he held from 2008 until Phillips 66 was spun-off from ConocoPhillips in 2012. He previously held a
series of executive positions with ConocoPhillips, including executive vice president, exploration and production, from 2007 to 2008, executive vice president, commercial, from 2006 to 2007, and executive vice president, planning, strategy and
corporate affairs from 2002 to 2006. Mr.&nbsp;Lowe is a director at Phillips 66, special executive advisor to Tudor, Pickering, Holt&nbsp;&amp; Co., and serves on the board of Agrium, Inc. Through these positions and his career in the oil and gas
industry, Mr.&nbsp;Lowe has gained valuable experience in identifying, assessing, and minimizing risk that can affect large oil and gas companies. These positions and his career have also provided him with the experience necessary for his role on
Apache&#146;s Management Development and Compensation and Stock Plan committees. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>WILLIAM C. MONTGOMERY</B> Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery has spent almost his
entire career working in the finance industry focusing on large cap energy companies. He currently serves as a managing director at Quantum Energy Partners where he provides advice on new and existing investments in the energy and power industries.
At Quantum, his duties include membership on the executive and investment committees, which set the firm&#146;s strategy and originate and oversee investments in the upstream, midstream, and oilfield service sectors of the oil and gas industry.
Previously, as a partner at Goldman, Sachs&nbsp;&amp; Co. for over eight years, he headed the Americas Natural Resources Group and was a member of the Investment Banking Services Leadership Group. Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery&#146;s contributions to the
Board will be aided by the knowledge and experience he gains from his current role at Quantum Energy Partners, which involves broad and deep exposure to key issues impacting the upstream, midstream, and oil services sectors. His contributions to the
Board will also be enhanced by his background as an investment banker, where he gained significant experience with the energy industry and energy-related capital markets. Apache will also benefit from the extensive relationships that
Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery has formed throughout his 22-year career serving various global energy companies. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>AMY H. NELSON </B>Ms.&nbsp;Nelson has devoted her
entire 22-year career to serving companies in the oil and gas industry.&nbsp;Ms.&nbsp;Nelson is the founder and president of Greenridge Advisors, LLC, an energy services and equipment consulting firm, where her consulting practice focuses on the
development, execution, and financing of growth strategies for her oil and gas industry clients.&nbsp;She advises her clients on strategy development, acquisition evaluation, and infrastructure development.&nbsp;Prior to Greenridge, Ms.&nbsp;Nelson
served as vice president of a private equity firm, SCF Partners, where she focused on investment strategy, investment execution, and portfolio company management.&nbsp;Previously, she also worked at Amoco Production Company in various roles
including as planning coordinator, project </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">10 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
manager, and as an engineer.&nbsp;Her various roles in the oil and gas industry have provided Ms.&nbsp;Nelson with valuable experience in the assessment and management of risk faced by oil and
gas companies. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>RODMAN D. PATTON</B> Prior to joining Apache&#146;s Board of Directors, for over 25 years, Mr.&nbsp;Patton held various executive
positions in the oil and gas investment banking industry. As a managing director at Merrill Lynch, First Boston (later Credit Suisse) and other investment banks, Mr.&nbsp;Patton gained extensive experience advising oil and gas companies on capital
structure, strategy, and direction. He also gained valuable experience in the assessment and management of risk faced by oil and gas companies. As a former investment banker and as chairman of NuStar GP&#146;s audit committee, Mr.&nbsp;Patton has
extensive financial reporting expertise, which serves him well in his role as a member of Apache&#146;s Audit Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>CHARLES J. PITMAN</B> Having
served in executive and director capacities at numerous oil and gas companies, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman has gained invaluable experience in and knowledge of the oil and gas industry. During his 24-year career at Amoco Corporation and BP Amoco plc,
Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served in a variety of leadership positions in the United States and multiple international locations, principally in the Middle East. Notably, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served as president of Amoco Egypt Oil Company from 1992 to 1996,
president of Amoco Eurasia Petroleum Company from 1997 to 1998, regional president BP Amoco plc - Middle East/Caspian/Egypt/India from December 1998 until his retirement in 1999. Most recently, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman has utilized his considerable
experience in international oil and gas by participating in oil and gas ventures in Russia and Algeria. Prior to joining Amoco, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman served in the United States Department of State as a foreign service officer and attorney-adviser. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">11 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_14"></A>DIRECTOR INDEPENDENCE </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">During 2013 and the first two months of 2014, the Board of Directors evaluated all business and charitable relationships between the Company and the
Company&#146;s non-employee directors (all directors other than Mr.&nbsp;Farris) and all other relevant facts and circumstances. As a result of the evaluation, the Board of Directors determined, as required by the Company&#146;s Governance
Principles, that each non-employee director is an independent director as defined by the standards for director independence established by applicable laws, rules, and listing standards including, without limitation, the standards for independent
directors established by The New York Stock Exchange, Inc. (&#147;NYSE&#148;), The NASDAQ National Market (&#147;NASDAQ&#148;), and the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;). The Company&#146;s Governance Principles are available on
the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Subject to some exceptions, these standards generally provide that a non-employee director will not be
independent if (a)&nbsp;the director is, or in the past three years has been, an employee of the Company; (b)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is, or in the past three years has been, an executive officer of the
Company; (c)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family has received more than $120,000 per year in direct compensation from the Company (other than for service as a director or for the immediate family member, as a
non-executive employee); (d)&nbsp;the director is an employee of or the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is employed as a partner of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP, the Company&#146;s independent registered public
accountants, or the director has an immediate family member who is a current employee of such firm and works in any capacity on the Company&#146;s audit, or the director or an immediate family member was within the last three years a partner or
employee of such firm and personally worked on the Company&#146;s audit within that time; (e)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is, or in the past three years has been, employed as an executive officer of a
company where an Apache executive officer serves on the compensation committee; or (f)&nbsp;the director or a member of the director&#146;s immediate family is an executive officer of a company that makes payments to, or receives payments from,
Apache in an amount which, in any twelve-month period during the past three years, exceeds the greater of $200,000 or two percent of the consolidated gross revenues of the company receiving the payment. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Lead Director </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company&#146;s Governance Principles
require that the independent (non-employee) directors meet in executive session at least twice each year and, in 2013, they met five times in executive session. These executive sessions are chaired by a lead director. Pursuant to the Company&#146;s
Governance Principles, the lead director is an independent director who is elected from time to time, but not less than annually, by the affirmative vote of a majority of the non-management directors. In addition to chairing the executive sessions,
the lead director discusses management&#146;s proposed meeting agenda with the other independent directors and reviews the approved meeting agenda with our chairman and chief executive officer, leads the discussion with our chief executive officer
following the independent directors&#146; executive sessions, ensures that the Board&#146;s individual group, and committee self-assessments are done annually, leads periodic discussions with other Board members and management concerning the
Board&#146;s information needs, and is available for discussions with major shareholders. Randolph M. Ferlic served as lead director from February 2011 until February 2013. Effective February 2013, Charles J. Pitman was elected as the Company&#146;s
lead director and effective February 2014, Mr.&nbsp;Pitman was re-elected as lead director. The role and responsibilities of the lead director and the method established for communication of concerns to the independent directors are included in the
Company&#146;s Governance Principles. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">12 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Reporting of Concerns to Independent Directors </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Anyone who has concerns about the Company may communicate those concerns to the independent directors. Such communication should be mailed to the
Company&#146;s corporate secretary at 2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100, Houston, Texas 77056-4400, who will forward such communications to the independent directors. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Board Leadership Structure and Risk Oversight </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Board Leadership Structure </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Throughout
much of Apache&#146;s history, the Company has ascribed to the traditional U.S. board leadership structure, under which our chief executive officer has also served as the chairman of our Board of Directors. From 1969 until 2002, both of these
positions were held by our founder, Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank. However, upon Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank&#146;s retirement as chief executive officer of the Company in 2002, Mr.&nbsp;Farris was appointed as the Company&#146;s chief executive officer and
Mr.&nbsp;Raymond Plank remained as the Company&#146;s chairman of the board. Upon Mr.&nbsp;Plank&#146;s retirement as chairman of the board in January 2009, Mr.&nbsp;Farris was appointed the Company&#146;s chairman of the board, once again unifying
the roles of chairman and chief executive officer. As Apache&#146;s history demonstrates, we believe it is important to maintain the flexibility to have either a combined or a separated chair and chief executive officer structure as circumstances
dictate.&nbsp;Each structure has served us well in the past. Currently, we believe that the efficiencies created by a combined position work best, especially when viewed in conjunction with our lead director, elected annually by our independent
directors, assuring strong board leadership.&nbsp;In particular, this structure helps to ensure clarity regarding leadership of the Company, allows the Company to speak with one voice and provides for efficient coordination of board action,
particularly in the event of crisis. The combination of the chairman&#146;s ability to call board meetings with the chief executive officer&#146;s intimate knowledge of our business, including our risk management framework, provides a strong
structure for the efficient operation of our board process and effective leadership of our Board overall. This structure avoids potential confusion as to leadership roles and duplication of efforts that can result from the roles being separated. It
also assists our chairman and chief executive officer in managing the Company and dealing with third parties more effectively on a day-to-day basis. Our Board regularly reviews all the aspects of our governance profile, including this one, and will
make changes as circumstances warrant. This is the model that the Company has utilized for much of its history, and we believe that it is the most effective way to lead the Company going forward. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Risk Oversight </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The goal of the
Company&#146;s risk management process is to understand and manage risk; management is responsible for identifying and managing the risks, while directors provide oversight to management in this process. Management identifies the significant risks
facing the Company and the approaches to mitigate such risk. The Company&#146;s Governance Principles state that in addition to its general oversight of management, the Board of Directors is responsible for a number of specific functions, including
assessing major risks facing the Company and reviewing options for their mitigation. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our Board of Directors has four standing independent committees:
Audit, Corporate Governance and Nominating, Management Development and Compensation, and Stock Plan. The Executive Committee was eliminated by the Board of Directors in May 2013. Our Audit Committee is primarily responsible for overseeing the
Company&#146;s risk management processes on behalf of the Board. The Audit Committee charter provides that the Audit Committee should discuss and consider the process by which senior management of the Company and the relevant departments assess and
manage the Company&#146;s exposure </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">13 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
to risk, and discuss the Company&#146;s major financial risk exposure and the steps management has taken to monitor, control, and report such exposures. In addition, the Audit Committee reports
to the Board of Directors, which also considers the Company&#146;s risk profile. The Audit Committee and the Board of Directors obtain input from management regarding the most significant risks facing the Company and the Company&#146;s risk
management strategy. The Audit Committee and the Board ensure that the risks undertaken are consistent with the Board&#146;s tolerance for risk. While the Board is responsible for setting, monitoring and maintaining the Company&#146;s risk
management policies and practices, the Company&#146;s executive officers and members of our management team are responsible for implementing and overseeing our day-to-day risk management processes. Additionally, the Board has created a Corporate
Risk Committee composed of members of our management team. The Corporate Risk Committee monitors and manages risks and is tasked with, among other things, ensuring sound policies, procedures, and practices are in place to address corporate-wide
management of risks. The Company believes that this division of responsibility is the most effective way to monitor and control risk. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In addition to the
oversight provided by our full Board of Directors, Audit Committee, executive officers and the members of our management team, including our Corporate Risk Committee, our independent (non-employee) directors hold regularly scheduled executive
sessions as often as they deem appropriate, but in any event at least twice each year. These executive sessions are chaired by our lead director, and provide an additional avenue through which we monitor the Company&#146;s risk exposure and policies
regarding risk management. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For risk considerations in our compensation programs, please read the Compensation Discussion and Analysis section included in
this proxy statement. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">14 </P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_15"></A>STANDING COMMITTEES AND MEETINGS OF THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board of Directors has an Audit Committee, a Corporate Governance and Nominating (&#147;CG&amp;N&#148;) Committee, a Management Development and
Compensation (&#147;MD&amp;C&#148;) Committee, a Stock Plan Committee, and until May 2013, an Executive Committee. Actions taken by these committees are reported to the Board of Directors at the next board meeting. During 2013, each of the
Company&#146;s current directors attended at least 75 percent of all meetings of the Board of Directors and committees of which he or she was a member. All directors attended the Company&#146;s 2013 annual meeting of shareholders held on
May&nbsp;16, 2013. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(8)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Montgomery served on the Stock Plan Committee until July 2013, at which time he was appointed to the CG&amp;N Committee. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">15 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Audit Committee </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit Committee assists the Board of Directors in fulfilling its oversight responsibility relating to (i)&nbsp;the integrity of the Company&#146;s
consolidated financial statements, accounting and financial reporting processes, and systems of internal controls over accounting and financial reporting; (ii)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; (iii)&nbsp;the
independent auditor&#146;s qualifications, independence, and performance, including sole authority for appointment, compensation, oversight, evaluation, and termination; (iv)&nbsp;the performance of the Company&#146;s internal audit function;
(v)&nbsp;the report of the Audit Committee required by the rules of the SEC, as included in this proxy statement; and (vi)&nbsp;the fulfillment of the other responsibilities set out in its charter. The Audit Committee charter, as adopted by the
Board of Directors and which reflects applicable SEC, NYSE and NASDAQ rules and regulations, is available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As described more fully above in &#147;Board Leadership Structure and Risk Oversight,&#148; the Audit Committee is also tasked with overseeing the guidelines,
policies, and controls governing the process by which management of the Company assesses and manages the Company&#146;s exposure to risk. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board of
Directors has determined that all members of the Audit Committee qualify as financial experts, as defined in Item&nbsp;407 of Regulation S-K under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, and each are considered &#147;financially literate&#148; under
NYSE rules. During 2013 and the first two months of 2014, the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the Audit Committee pursuant to the rules of the SEC, NYSE and NASDAQ governing audit committees. Based on this review, the Board of
Directors confirmed that all members of the Audit Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the SEC, NYSE and NASDAQ rules. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>CG&amp;N Committee
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The duties of the CG&amp;N Committee include recommending to the Board of Directors the slate of director nominees submitted to the shareholders for
election at each annual meeting and proposing qualified candidates to fill vacancies on the Board of Directors. The CG&amp;N Committee is also responsible for developing corporate governance principles for the Company, reviewing related party
transactions, and overseeing the evaluation of the Board of Directors. During 2013 and the first two months of 2014, the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the CG&amp;N Committee pursuant to the rules of the NYSE and NASDAQ governing
nominating and governance committees. Based on this review, the Board of Directors confirmed that all members of the CG&amp;N Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the NYSE and NASDAQ rules. The CG&amp;N Committee charter, as adopted by the
Board of Directors, is available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The CG&amp;N Committee considers director nominee recommendations
from executive officers of the Company, independent members of the Board and shareholders of the Company, as well as recommendations from other interested parties. The CG&amp;N Committee may also retain an outside search firm to assist it in finding
appropriate nominee candidates. Shareholder recommendations for director nominees received by Apache&#146;s corporate secretary (at the address for submitting shareholder proposals and nominations set forth under the heading &#147;Future Shareholder
Proposals and Director Nominations&#148; below) are forwarded to the CG&amp;N Committee for consideration. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">16 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>MD&amp;C Committee </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The MD&amp;C Committee reviews the Company&#146;s management resources and structure and administers the Company&#146;s compensation programs and retirement,
stock purchase and similar plans. Under the provisions of its charter, the MD&amp;C Committee may, at its discretion and if allowed by applicable laws or regulations, delegate all or a portion of its duties and responsibilities to a subcommittee of
the MD&amp;C Committee composed of at least two members. During 2013 and the first two months of 2014, the Board of Directors reviewed the composition of the MD&amp;C Committee pursuant to the rules of the NYSE and NASDAQ governing compensation
committees. Based on this review, the Board of Directors confirmed that all members of the MD&amp;C Committee are &#147;independent&#148; under the NYSE and NASDAQ rules. The MD&amp;C Committee charter, as adopted by the Board of Directors, is
available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Stock Plan Committee </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The principal purpose of the Stock Plan Committee is to assist the Board of Directors in the discharge of its responsibilities related to equity-based
compensation for the Company&#146;s employees, including the named executive officers. The Stock Plan Committee charter, as adopted by the Board of Directors, is available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The members of the Stock Plan Committee are &#147;outside directors&#148; as defined by applicable federal tax law or regulations of the Internal Revenue
Service. The duties of the Stock Plan Committee include (i)&nbsp;administration of the Company&#146;s equity-based compensation plans and programs and approval, award, and administration of grants made thereunder, (ii)&nbsp;certification of
performance goals and their achievement, (iii)&nbsp;making recommendations to the Board of Directors with respect to the Company&#146;s equity-based compensation plans and programs, and (iv)&nbsp;any other duties and responsibilities expressly
delegated to the Stock Plan Committee by the Board of Directors relating to equity-based compensation plans and programs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Executive Committee </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Prior to its elimination by the Board of Directors in May 2013, the Executive Committee was vested with the authority to exercise the full power of the Board
of Directors, within established policies, in the intervals between meetings of the Board of Directors. In addition to the general authority vested in it, the Executive Committee was, from time to time, vested with specific powers and authority by
resolution of the Board of Directors. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Committee Charters </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As noted above, you can access electronic copies of the charters of the Audit Committee, CG&amp;N Committee, MD&amp;C Committee, and Stock Plan Committee of
the Board of Directors on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). Also available on the Company&#146;s website are our Governance Principles and our Code of Business Conduct, which meets the requirements of a code of ethics under applicable
SEC regulations and NYSE and NASDAQ standards. You may request printed copies of any of these documents by writing to Apache&#146;s corporate secretary at 2000 Post Oak Boulevard, Suite 100, Houston, Texas 77056-4400. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">17 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_16"></A>CRITERIA FOR NEW BOARD MEMBERS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>AND RE-ELECTION OF BOARD MEMBERS </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The
CG&amp;N Committee considers the following criteria in recommending new nominees or the re-election of directors to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors and its committees: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Expertise and perspective needed to govern the business and strengthen and support senior management &#151; for example: strong financial expertise, knowledge of international operations, or knowledge of the petroleum
industry and/or related industries. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Sound business judgment and a sufficiently broad perspective to make meaningful contributions. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Interest and enthusiasm in the Company and a commitment to become involved in its future. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The time and energy to meet Board of Directors commitments. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Ability to constructively participate in discussions, with the capacity to quickly understand and evaluate complex and diverse issues. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Dedication to the highest ethical standards. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Supportive of management, but independent, objective, and willing to question and challenge both openly and in private exchanges. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">An awareness of the dynamics of change and a willingness to anticipate and explore opportunities. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">All
decisions to recommend the nomination of a new nominee for election to the Board of Directors or for the re-election of a director are within the sole discretion of the CG&amp;N Committee. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">All director candidates are evaluated, and the decision of whether or not to nominate a particular candidate is made, based solely on Company- and work-related
factors and not with regard to a candidate&#146;s or director&#146;s inclusion in any protected class or group identified in the Company&#146;s anti-discrimination policy. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The above criteria and guidelines, together with the section of the Company&#146;s Governance Principles entitled &#147;Qualifications of Board Members&#148;
constitute the policy of the CG&amp;N Committee regarding the recommendation of new nominees or the re-election of directors to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors or its committees. The Company&#146;s Governance Principles are available on the
Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Diversity </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Company policy precludes directors and employees from discriminating against any protected group. Company policy also precludes directors and employees from
basing work-related decisions on anything other than work-relevant criteria.&nbsp;The Company&#146;s approach to diversity complements these policies without conflicting with them. Our status as a global company makes the need for board diversity in
all its aspects essential to our business.&nbsp;Our criteria for board selection, summarized in this section, operates as our diversity policy. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">18 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_17"></A>REPORT OF THE AUDIT COMMITTEE </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>The following report of the Audit Committee of the Company shall not be deemed to be &#147;soliciting material&#148; or to be &#147;filed&#148; with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, nor shall this report be incorporated by reference into any filing made by the Company under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, or the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit Committee is operated under a charter that specifies the scope of the Committee&#146;s responsibilities. The charter, which is reviewed annually and
available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com), was last amended effective May&nbsp;16, 2013. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board of Directors has determined that all
four members of the Committee are independent based upon the standards adopted by the Board, which incorporate the independence requirements under applicable laws, rules and regulations, including the listing standards of the New York Stock Exchange
and the NASDAQ National Market and Rule 10A-3 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company&#146;s management has the primary
responsibility for preparing the Company&#146;s financial statements, managing the accounting and financial reporting processes, devising and maintaining the systems of internal controls over financial reporting, and assessing the effectiveness of
internal controls over financial reporting. Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP, Apache&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm (the &#147;independent auditors&#148;), is responsible for the integrated audit of the consolidated financial
statements and auditing the Company&#146;s internal controls over financial reporting. The Committee&#146;s responsibility is to monitor and oversee these processes and procedures on behalf of the Board of Directors. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit Committee held ten meetings during fiscal year 2013, including the five in-person meetings referenced below. The meetings of the Audit Committee are
designed to facilitate and encourage communication among the Audit Committee, the Company, the Company&#146;s internal audit function, and the Company&#146;s independent auditors. Meeting agendas are set based upon the Audit Committee Charter and
also include suggested topics from committee members and/or other relevant topics. At four of the five Audit Committee meetings held in person during 2013, the Committee met with the internal auditors and the independent auditors, with and without
management present, to discuss the results of their examinations, their evaluations of the Company&#146;s internal controls, including internal controls over financial reporting, and the overall quality of the Company&#146;s financial reporting.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Committee is responsible for oversight of the qualifications, performance, and independence of the Company&#146;s independent auditors and annually
determines whether to retain the Company&#146;s current independent auditors or retain another auditor. In doing so, the Audit Committee takes into consideration a number of factors, including the historical and recent performance of the independent
auditors and lead partner, its global capabilities, its knowledge of the Company&#146;s operations and industry, external data relating to audit quality and performance, including recent Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States)
(&#147;PCAOB&#148;) reports, and independence. The Audit Committee recognizes the importance of maintaining the independence of the Company&#146;s independent auditors, in both fact and appearance. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit Committee discussed with the Company&#146;s internal auditors and the independent auditors the overall scope and plans for their respective audits.
In addition, the Audit Committee reviewed with the independent auditors, which is responsible for expressing an opinion on the conformity of the Company&#146;s audited consolidated financial statements with U.S. generally accepted accounting
principles, its judgments as to the quality, not just the acceptability, of the Company&#146;s accounting principles and such other matters as are required to be discussed with the Audit Committee by the standards of the PCAOB,
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">19 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
including PCOAB Auditing Standard No.&nbsp;16, <I>Communications With Audit Committees,</I> the rules of the Securities and Exchange Commission, and other applicable regulations. In addition, the
Audit Committee has discussed with the independent auditors the firm&#146;s independence from Company management and the Company, including the matters in the letter from the firm required by PCAOB Rule 3526, <I>Communication with Audit Committees
Concerning Independence</I>, and considered the compatibility of non-audit services with the independent auditors&#146; independence. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit Committee
also reviewed and discussed together with management, the internal auditors, and the independent auditors the Company&#146;s audited consolidated financial statements included in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended
December&nbsp;31, 2013, including the clarity of disclosures in the financial statements, the results of management&#146;s assessment of the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal controls over financial reporting, and the independent
auditors&#146; audit of the Company&#146;s internal controls over financial reporting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In reliance on the reviews and discussions referred to above, the
Audit Committee recommended to the Board of Directors, and the Board of Directors has approved, that the audited consolidated financial statements and management&#146;s assessment of the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal controls over
financial reporting be included in the Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013, filed by the Company with the Securities and Exchange Commission. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
