</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">From time to time we also award special achievement bonuses, separate and apart from the annual bonus, where circumstances
warrant. During 2013, no special achievement bonuses were awarded to any NEO. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_20a"></A>Long-Term Compensation Awards - Summary
</B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Long-term, equity-based compensation is
regularly made available to substantially all of our employees to ensure a company-wide ethic of ownership and entrepreneurialism. Properly designed long-term, equity-based compensation aligns the interests of executive officers and employees with
those of our shareholders and plays an important role in our overall compensation structure. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We annually grant to our executive officers a combination of
equity instruments (RSUs, stock options, TSR Shares or other Performance Shares), the overall grant value of which is based on a hierarchical multiple of salary. The multiple of salary for each executive is determined based on the executive&#146;s
level in the organization and is adjusted periodically as necessary to align the total compensation of our executives with the market. The multiples for long-term compensation increase as the level of responsibility rises. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">47 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">At the beginning of 2013, long-term compensation planned to be awarded to our executive officers was to be
apportioned in accordance with targeted grant date values as follows: TSR Shares (35 percent), RSUs (35 percent), and stock options (30 percent). TSR shares were issued in January, with the remainder normally to be issued in May. In anticipation of
our impending say-on-pay vote, we reduced the amount of RSUs and stock options issued to our top three NEOs, including our CEO, in order to reduce their total compensation and increase the amount of their equity based compensation that was
performance related. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>TSR Shares </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Each January, our
NEOs receive TSR Shares under our TSR Program. Under the TSR Program: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">We issue conditional awards to each executive officer based on a target percentage of the grantee&#146;s annual base salary; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:8pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Each TSR Program has a three-year performance period at the end of which a calculation of TSR performance is determined for Apache and each member of the Performance Peer Group; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:8pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Our TSR performance is directly ranked against the Performance Peer Group, resulting in the application of a payout factor to the target number of TSR Shares to derive the adjusted number of shares that will actually be
paid at the end of the performance period; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:8pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">If a payout is warranted, for 2013, 50 percent of the resulting shares are delivered at the end of the three-year performance period, with the remaining 50 percent vesting equally over the following two years;
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Officers must be employed at the time of each vesting to receive vested shares; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">If a change of control and a recipient&#146;s involuntary termination or voluntary termination with cause (double trigger) occur (i)&nbsp;prior to the calculation of performance, the TSR is calculated and our TSR
performance is ranked within the Performance Peer Group as of the date of termination; (ii)&nbsp;following the calculation of performance, the entire amount of the earned award vests as of the date of termination. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Performance Peer Group for our 2013 TSR Program was the same as for 2012<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">xi</SUP>. Through 2013, we used an
expanded peer group for this purpose only. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Restricted Stock Units </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Each May through 2013, our employees including our NEOs received RSUs. Generally, the RSUs: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Are granted to substantially our entire employee population, including our executive officers, based on a target percentage of the grantee&#146;s then annual base salary; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Vest ratably over four years; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Upon vesting, allow each grantee to receive one share of common stock for each RSU; and </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Require a double trigger for accelerated vesting (both a change of control and a recipient&#146;s involuntary termination or voluntary termination with cause). </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">48 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Stock Options </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Each May through 2013, our NEOs also received stock options. Generally, our stock options: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Are granted to our NEOs based on a target percentage of the grantee&#146;s then annual base salary; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Become exercisable ratably over a four-year period; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Have an exercise price equal to the closing price of our common stock on the date of grant and expire 10 years after grant; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Require a double trigger for accelerated vesting (both a change of control and a recipient&#146;s involuntary termination or voluntary termination with cause); and </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Cannot be repriced or reset or exchanged for cash, if they are underwater (exercise price is greater than current stock price). </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:36pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_21a"></A>Long-Term Compensation Awards &#150; 2013 Decisions </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In 2013, we granted TSR Shares, RSUs, and stock
options to the NEOs. Originally, we planned the grant date value of long-term compensation for all NEOs to be allocated as follows: 35 percent TSR Shares, 35 percent RSUs, and 30 percent stock options. However, in May 2013, the Board determined that
the remaining unissued equity awards (RSUs and stock options) for Mr.&nbsp;Farris, Mr.&nbsp;Plank, and Mr.&nbsp;Eichler would be reduced. As a large portion of our equity awards for 2013 had already been granted in January, by the time our
say-on-pay vote was developing in May 2013, the May RSU and option grants were the only remaining scheduled grants for 2013. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under our 2013 TSR Program,
a rank of one results in a multiple of 2.0 with the multiple grading down to 0.55 for a ranking of 15 (out of 19), and a multiple of 0.0 for a ranking in the bottom quartile as follows: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Note that the targeted grant date values of long-term compensation and the actual grant date values shown in the
tables in this proxy vary somewhat due to the prospective nature of targets. The amounts that will be actually realized by the NEOs from these awards may differ substantially from the grant date values. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>TSR Share Results: Earlier TSR Programs </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The performance
period for the 2011 TSR Program began on January&nbsp;1, 2011, and ended on December&nbsp;31, 2013. Apache was ranked in the bottom 10 percent amongst its peer group, which resulted in a zero payout and the cancellation and forfeiture of the grants
under this program for all eligible employees. The 2010 TSR Plan also yielded a zero payout. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_22a"></A>Compensation Decisions With
Respect to 2014 </B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Base Salary </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Effective January&nbsp;1, 2014, base salaries were changed for two NEOs related to the following role changes: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Eichler became Executive Advisor to the Chairman and assumed the role of chief executive officer for Kitimat LNG resulting in a base salary adjustment from $900,000 to $650,000. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Voytovich became chief operating officer, international, resulting in an increase from $675,000 to $725,000. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>2014 Annual Bonus Structure </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Consistent with the 2013
plan, the weightings for the corporate performance element of the 2014 plan are again based 70 percent on corporate objectives and 30 percent on management objectives. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Due to the recent transformation in our portfolio, we have revised the corporate objectives to include a combination of operational metrics imperative to the
2014 success of our E&amp;P business and strategic objectives tailored specifically to our plan for 2014. The corporate objectives established for 2014 include metrics related to production growth per share, reserves replacement, cash flow per
barrel sold, the after-tax rate of return on the 2014 drilling program, and health, safety, security and environmental objectives. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The structure of the
2014 management objectives remains the same as the 2013 objectives, with each business unit defining specific objectives for the year tailored to the 2014 plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Long-Term Compensation Awards in 2014 </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As an outcome of
our meetings with our shareholders in 2013, we determined that a greater emphasis should be placed on performance-based equity awards for 2014. The weight of performance-based equity has been increased to two-thirds of the awards for the CEO and
half of the awards for all other NEOs. Stock options have been suspended from the awards for 2014. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">During our shareholder engagement process we found
that most of our shareholders view our peer group to be the eight to ten E&amp;P companies closest to us in size (as measured by market cap or assets). While many of our shareholders understood the desire to expand our peer group for TSR purposes in
order to have larger statistical validity, a number of our shareholders had negative reactions to the expanded </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">50 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">
group we used for TSR, as the expansion required us to include increasingly dissimilar companies. We determined that the larger TSR group did not deliver a materially different outcome and have
elected for the 2014 TSR program to unify our peer group for both pay assessment and TSR purposes. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The 2014 TSR Program is similar to the 2013 TSR
Program with some modifications. Under our 2014 TSR Program we have a more focused group of 12 peer companies including ourselves. A TSR rank of number one in the peer group results in a multiple of 2.00 times target with the multiple grading down
to 0.40 for a ranking of 9, and a multiple of 0.0 for a ranking below 9 as shown below. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The TSRs have a cap at target payout in the event absolute TSR for Apache is negative over the performance period,
notwithstanding the relative performance of the shares. The shares will vest 50 percent at the end of the three-year performance period, with the remaining 50 percent vesting one year later. This vesting schedule was reduced from prior years to
align with the four-year vesting timeframe of our other equity compensation programs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In addition to the 2014 TSR Program, a new form of performance
shares has been introduced for 2014 that is based on business performance results coinciding with our corporate objectives as stated above. The overall results of the objectives will be calculated at the end of 2014 and, if a payout is warranted,
applied to the target number of RSUs awarded. The actual amount of shares awarded will be between 0 percent and 150 percent of target. The initial 2014 program is designed to measure performance over a one-year period as we emerge from our portfolio
restructuring period, however, the MD&amp;C Committee is considering longer performance periods for future programs. The shares will vest 50 percent at the end of three years, with the remaining 50 percent vesting at the end of four years. The
executive must remain employed with Apache on the vesting date to receive the vested shares. These internal business factors combined with relative TSR provide for a more balanced perspective of overall company performance. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">51 </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>Composition of Long-Term Compensation for Other NEOs </B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:14pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" BGCOLOR="#e5e5e5"><B><A NAME="tx616560_23a"></A>OUR EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION DECISION MAKING PROCESS</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_24a"></A>Role of the Board of Directors </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Compensation decision making for executives is both
a core Board responsibility and an effective tool for shaping our strategy and performance. The MD&amp;C Committee provides recommendations to the independent members of the Board for the CEO&#146;s compensation and to the entire Board for other
NEOs&#146; compensation, including base salary, annual cash incentive bonus, and long-term compensation multiples and components. The Board (or the independent members of the Board, as the case may be) actively reviews the recommendations and
approves them as recommended or with modifications. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_25a"></A>Role of the Management Development and Compensation Committee </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The MD&amp;C Committee, which met 8 times in 2013,
plays a key role in the Board&#146;s compensation oversight and decision making. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The MD&amp;C Committee, on behalf of the Board, is responsible for
reviewing and assessing the effectiveness of our compensation programs in general, and our executive compensation programs in particular. In performing these duties, the MD&amp;C Committee reviews compensation programs and policies to avoid the
incentivizing of excessive risk. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s key responsibilities are: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">To review our goals and objectives, evaluate performance in light of such goals, and recommend the CEO&#146;s compensation to the Board for approval by the independent directors. This review is handled in independent
sessions. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">52 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">To make recommendations to the Board concerning the base salary, incentive and equity-based compensation plans for executive officers other than the CEO. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">To review and recommend to the Board broad-based, long-term compensation programs for executive and non-executive employees. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Each of the MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s four members meets the independence requirements of the New York Stock Exchange and NASDAQ listing standards. The
MD&amp;C Committee&#146;s charter is available on our website. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_26a"></A>Role of the Stock Plan Committee </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The principal purpose of the Stock Plan Committee,
which met 8 times in 2013, is to assist the Board in the discharge of its responsibilities relating to equity-based compensation of our employees. The Stock Plan Committee&#146;s key responsibilities are: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Administration of our equity-based compensation plans and programs and the approval, award, and administration of grants under the same, including certification of performance goals and their achievement.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Make recommendations to the Board with respect to our equity-based compensation plans and programs. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Prepare a summary of the grants and awards made under our equity-based compensation plans and programs for the MD&amp;C Committee for use in our proxy statement. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Any other duties or responsibilities expressly delegated to the Stock Plan Committee by the Board from time to time relating to our equity-based compensation plans and programs. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Each member of the Stock Plan Committee meets the independence requirements of the New York Stock Exchange and NASDAQ listing standards and is an outside
director within the meaning of Section&nbsp;
162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code. The Stock Plan Committee&#146;s charter is available on our website. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_27a"></A>Role of the
Compensation Consultant </B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board and the
MD&amp;C Committee have broad access to information to perform their compensation functions. The Board has authorized the MD&amp;C Committee to retain an independent compensation consultant. In September 2013, the MD&amp;C Committee engaged Meridian
Compensation Partners (the &#147;Consultant&#148;), to provide independent compensation advice and data to the MD&amp;C Committee and the Board.&nbsp;Prior to this time, the MD&amp;C Committee retained the services of Pearl Meyer&nbsp;&amp; Partners
(&#147;PMP&#148;). The Consultant performs an annual review of executive total compensation relative to the market. In addition, the Consultant assesses the competitiveness of our compensation programs versus the practices of our compensation peers
and reviews these programs for any potential risk. Except for limited work for management in connection with the Consultant&#146;s published industry-specific surveys, for which the Consultant received <I>de minimis</I> compensation, neither the
Consultant nor PMP provided any services to Apache other than the executive compensation-related services to the Board. After its review, the MD&amp;C Committee determined that no conflict of interest arose from the work performed by the Consultant.
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">53 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Also, each year the MD&amp;C Committee reviews the independence of the Consultant to ensure that the Consultant
is indeed independent. Among other things, this review includes a certification from the Consultant in which the Committee is provided with written evidence of compliance with the Consultant&#146;s own rules regarding independence. This
certification from the Consultant was provided to the MD&amp;C Committee, and after its review, the MD&amp;C Committee determined that both the Consultant and PMP were independent. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_28a"></A>Role of Management </B></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In addition to the use of the Consultant, the
MD&amp;C Committee receives compensation recommendations and evaluations of the executive group from the CEO. The MD&amp;C Committee, along with each of the independent directors, is authorized by the Board to obtain information from and work
directly with any employee in fulfilling its responsibilities. Our executive vice president of human resources prepares information and materials for the CEO and the MD&amp;C Committee for the exercise of their distinct, but interrelated,
compensation responsibilities. The MD&amp;C Committee also utilizes the data provided by the Consultant, including recommendations for the associated compensation values derived from their reports. The MD&amp;C Committee carefully considers the
CEO&#146;s recommendations on these matters, reaches final determination, and reports these outcomes to the Board in the form of recommended actions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:13pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="tx616560_29a">
</A>Risk Considerations in Our Compensation Programs </B></P> <P STYLE="line-height:5.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our MD&amp;C Committee has discussed the concept of risk as it relates to our compensation programs, and the MD&amp;C Committee does not believe our
compensation programs encourage excessive or inappropriate risk taking. The MD&amp;C Committee with assistance of the Consultant arrived at this conclusion for the following reasons: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Our employees receive both fixed and variable compensation. The fixed (salary) portion provides a steady income regardless of the Company&#146;s stock performance. This allows executives to focus on the Company&#146;s
business without an excessive focus on the Company&#146;s stock price performance. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The goals and objectives for the annual cash incentive bonus are set to avoid overweighting any single factor that, if not achieved, would result in the loss of a large percentage of compensation. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Our stock options and restricted stock units for executives generally vest over four years, which discourages short-term risk taking. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Our equity ownership requirements encourage a long-term perspective by our executives. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">All of our executives&#146; unvested long-term equity compensation is forfeited upon voluntary termination, which encourages our executives to remain with the Company and maintain a long-term focus. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Our incentive programs have been in place for many years, and we have seen no evidence that they encourage excessive risk taking. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:12pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Essentially all of our employees participate in our equity-based compensation programs, regardless of business unit which encourages consistent behavior across the Company. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">54 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:14pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="100%"></TD></TR>


<TR BGCOLOR="#bfbfbf" STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:14pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" BGCOLOR="#e5e5e5"><B><A NAME="tx616560_30a"></A>TAX LEGISLATION RELATED TO COMPENSATION</B></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended, imposes a limit, with certain exceptions, on the amount
that a publicly held corporation may deduct in any tax year commencing on or after January&nbsp;1, 1994, for the compensation paid or accrued with respect to its chief executive officer and its three highest compensated officers for the year (other
than the principal executive officer or the principal financial officer). The MD&amp;C Committee continues to review our compensation plans based upon these regulations and, from time to time, determines what further actions or changes to our
compensation plans, if any, would be appropriate. It is the intention of the MD&amp;C Committee for us to receive shareholder approval for all future stock-based compensation plans so that they may qualify for the performance-based compensation
exemption. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our 2005 Stock Option Plan, 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan (including the 2011 TSR Program), and 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan
(including the 2012 and 2013 TSR Programs) were approved by our shareholders and grants made under such plans qualify as &#147;performance-based&#148; under the regulations. Our existing annual cash incentive compensation plan, special achievement
bonuses, and 2000 Stock Option Plan do not meet the requirements of the regulations, as the shareholder approvals necessary for exemption were not sought. However, these plans operate similarly to prior or other existing plans and are designed to
reward the contribution and performance of employees and to provide a meaningful incentive for achieving Apache&#146;s goals, which in turn enhances shareholder value. No further grants can be made under the 2000 and 2005 Stock Option Plans, or the
2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan. While the MD&amp;C Committee cannot predict with certainty how our compensation policies may be further affected by this limitation, it is anticipated that executive compensation paid or accrued pursuant to our
compensation plans that have not met the requirements of the regulations will not result in any material loss of tax deductions in the foreseeable future. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Internal Revenue Code section 409A requires &#147;nonqualified deferred compensation plans&#148; to meet requirements in order to avoid acceleration of the
recipient&#146;s federal income taxation of the deferred compensation. The Internal Revenue Service issued final regulations in April 2007 regarding the application of Section&nbsp;409A, which were generally effective January&nbsp;1, 2009. Prior to
effectiveness, companies were expected to comply in &#147;good faith&#148; with the statute, taking note of the interim guidance issued by the Internal Revenue Service. We amended several of our benefit plans in order for them to be exempt from
Section&nbsp;409A, while we continue to provide benefits through several plans that remain subject to Section&nbsp;409A. The terms of these plans were amended before January&nbsp;1, 2009, as necessary, and are intended to meet the requirements of
the final regulations. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">55 </P>

with management the Compensation Discussion and Analysis set forth above, and based upon such review and discussion, recommended to the Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in this proxy statement. </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_25"></A>SUMMARY COMPENSATION TABLE </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The table below summarizes the compensation for the individuals listed below for all services rendered to the Company and its subsidiaries during fiscal years
2013, 2012 and 2011. The persons included in this table are the Company&#146;s principal executive officer, principal financial officer, and the three other most highly compensated executive officers (the &#147;Named Executive Officers&#148;) who
served as executive officers of the Company during 2013. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:8pt" ALIGN="center">

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">57 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>All Other Compensation </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Officers participate in two qualified retirement plans. The 401(k) Savings Plan provides a match up to the first six percent of base pay and incentive bonus.
The Money Purchase Retirement Plan provides an annual eight percent company contribution into the same investment choices as the 401(k) Savings Plan with the exception of Company stock. Additionally, officers can elect to participate in the
Non-Qualified Retirement/Savings Plan to defer beyond the limits in the 401(k) Savings Plan and continue Company contributions which exceed the limits in the qualified plans. The investment choices mirror those in the 401(k) Savings Plan and the
Money Purchase Retirement Plan. The Deferred Delivery Plan allows officers the ability to defer income in the form of deferred units from the vesting of restricted stock units under the Company&#146;s 2007 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan and 2011
Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan. The contributions into both non-qualified plans are reported in the Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation Table. The Company does not have a defined benefit plan for U.S. employees. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Apache provides U.S. employees with two times their base salary under group term life insurance. Executives receive the first $50,000 of coverage under the
same group term life insurance plan, and the remaining amount to bring them up to two times salary is provided in the form of whole life insurance policies. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Board requires G. Steven Farris to use the Company&#146;s aircraft for all air travel for security reasons and to facilitate efficient business travel,
unless good business judgment requires otherwise. Even though the Company considers these costs a necessary business expense rather than a perquisite for Mr.&nbsp;Farris, in line with SEC guidance, the following table includes the amounts
attributable to each Named Executive Officer&#146;s personal aircraft usage. Executives are not reimbursed for the taxes on the income attributable to the personal use of corporate aircraft. The methodology for the valuation of non-integral use of
corporate aircraft for disclosure in the Summary Compensation Table, in compliance with SEC guidance, calculates the incremental cost to the Company for personal use of the aircraft based on the cost of fuel and oil per hour of flight; trip-related
inspections, repairs and maintenance; crew travel expenses; on-board catering; trip-related flight planning services; landing, parking, and hanger fees; supplies; passenger ground transportation; and other variable costs. Additionally, the value of
trips attributable to philanthropic interests was included, even though they are seen as contributing to the goodwill of the Company. In addition, Standard Industry Fare Level (&#147;SIFL&#148;) tables, published by the Internal Revenue Service, are
used to determine the amount of compensation income that is imputed to the executive for tax purposes for personal use of corporate aircraft. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In addition
to the benefits for which all employees are eligible, the Company also covers the cost of an annual physical and the full cost of enhanced long-term disability coverage for executive officers. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company provides various forms of compensation related to expatriate assignment that differ according to location and term of assignment, including:
foreign service premium, foreign assignment tax equalization, location pay, housing and utilities, home leave and travel, goods and services allowance, relocation expense, and tax return and visa preparation. These items have been reflected in the
following table under Foreign Assignment Allowances for the amounts that pertain to Mr.&nbsp;Eichler and to Mr.&nbsp;Voytovich. Mr.&nbsp;Eichler, as executive vice president &#151; Egypt, resided in Egypt from 2007 to June 2009. Mr.&nbsp;Voytovich,
as region vice president &#151; Egypt, resided in Egypt from June 2009 to February 2012. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">58 </P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(c)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Executives assigned to foreign countries typically incur a change in their overall tax liability because most of the components of assignment compensation that are provided in addition to base salary are taxable in the
United States and in the foreign country. Therefore, the Company&#146;s expatriate assignment policy provides that it will be responsible for any additional foreign or U.S. taxes due as a direct result of the international assignment and the
executive remains financially responsible for the tax which he/she would have incurred if he/she had continued to live and work in the United States.&nbsp;Pursuant to this policy, the Company withheld from Mr.&nbsp;Eichler&#146;s and Mr.
Voytovich&#146;s compensation an amount equivalent to the taxes that would have been due had he remained in the United States.&nbsp;Those funds were used to help pay taxes due in the United States and in Egypt during the period of his foreign
assignment.&nbsp;The Company paid taxes due in excess of Mr.&nbsp;Eichler&#146;s and Mr. Voytovich&#146;s withholding that were incurred as a result of his foreign assignment. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(d)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">This amount for 2012 includes $6,983 in tax credits related to foreign assignment and $750 for tax return preparation. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_26"></A>GRANTS OF PLAN BASED AWARDS TABLE </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The table below provides supplemental information relating to the Company&#146;s grants of stock options and restricted stock units during fiscal year 2013 to
the Named Executive Officers. There were no stock appreciation rights granted during fiscal year 2013. Also included, in compliance with SEC rules on disclosure of executive compensation, is information relating to the estimated grant date fair
value of the grants. For stock options, the estimated fair value is based upon principles of the Black-Scholes option pricing model. The Black-Scholes model utilizes numerous arbitrary assumptions about financial variables such as interest rates,
stock price volatility and future dividend yield. Neither the values reflected in the table nor the assumptions utilized in arriving at the values should be considered indicative of future stock performance. </P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Reflects estimated possible payouts under the Company&#146;s annual incentive compensation plan. The estimated amounts are calculated based on the applicable annual bonus target and base salary earnings for each Named
Executive Officer in effect for the 2013 measurement period. Beginning with the 2012 annual incentive bonus awards, a maximum payout not to exceed 200 percent of target was established. The Company&#146;s annual incentive compensation plan does not
contain thresholds. Actual incentive bonus awards granted for 2013 are reflected in the &#147;Non-Equity Incentive Plan Compensation&#148; column of the Summary Compensation Table. </TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The target number assumes that the multiple described below is 1.00, while the maximum number assumes a multiple of 2.00. The threshold level shown is zero because Company performance in the bottom quartile results in
no payout. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">On November&nbsp;12, 2012, pursuant to the 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan, the Company established the 2013 Performance Program Specifications for all professional and management employees (excluding Egyptian
nationals and non-exempt support staff and non-supervisory field staff) who are employed on or before December&nbsp;31, 2012. These employees, including the executives named in the Summary Compensation Table, were granted the right to receive
restricted stock units (&#147;RSUs&#148;), the number of which will be determined and for which vesting will begin on December&nbsp;31, 2015 based on the Company&#146;s total shareholder return (&#147;TSR&#148;) as compared to a peer group of 18
companies. At the conclusion of the three-year performance period, which began on January&nbsp;1, 2013 and ends on December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company&#146;s performance will be directly ranked within the peer group, resulting in the
</TD></TR></TABLE> <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="right"><I>(footnotes continued on following page) </I></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right">0.55</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right">0.00</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:3%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">If the Company&#146;s TSR ranks from 1 to 15, vesting will begin on December&nbsp;31, 2015, with 50 percent of
the adjusted number of RSUs vesting immediately, 25 percent vesting as of December&nbsp;31, 2016, and 25 percent vesting as of December&nbsp;31, 2017. If the Company ranks from 16 to 19, none of the conditional RSUs will vest. Employees must be
employed during the entire performance period and on the date of vesting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:3%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">TSR is determined by dividing (i)&nbsp;the sum of the cumulative
amount of a company&#146;s dividends for the performance period (assuming same-day reinvestment into the company&#146;s common stock on the ex-dividend date) and the share price of the company at the end of the performance period minus the share
price at the beginning of the performance period by (ii)&nbsp;the share price at the beginning of the performance period. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">This column reflects the number of RSUs granted under the terms of the 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan on May&nbsp;16, 2013. The grant date fair value of these awards, calculated in accordance with FAS 123R, is
based on a closing price of the Company&#146;s common stock on the date of grant. Except as discussed below, such RSUs are generally non-transferable, vest ratably over four years, and no dividends are paid on such units until vested.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">This column sets forth the number of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock subject to options granted under the terms of the 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan. The options granted under the terms of the 2011
Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan are generally nontransferable and become exercisable ratably over four years. The options were granted for a term of ten years, subject to earlier termination in specific circumstances related to termination of
employment, and are not intended to qualify as incentive stock options under Section&nbsp;422 of the Internal Revenue Code. The exercise price and any withholding tax requirements may be paid by cash and/or delivery or attestation of already-owned
shares of the Company&#146;s common stock. The Company&#146;s stock option plans, including the 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan, are administered by the Stock Plan Committee of the Company&#146;s Board of Directors. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:3%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Options granted under the 2011 Omnibus Equity Compensation Plan are subject to appropriate adjustment in the event of reorganization, stock
split, stock dividend, combination of shares, merger, consolidation or other recapitalization of the Company. Upon both a change of control of the Company and termination of employment, all outstanding options become automatically vested so as to
make all such options fully vested and exercisable as of the date of such change of control. A change of control occurs when a person, partnership or corporation acting in concert, or any or all of them, acquires more than 20 percent of the
Company&#146;s outstanding voting securities. A change of control shall not occur if, prior to the acquisition of more than 20 percent of the Company&#146;s voting securities, such persons, partnerships or corporations are solicited to do so by the
Company&#146;s Board of Directors. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The exercise price is the closing price per share of the Company&#146;s common stock on the date of grant, as reported on The New York Exchange, Inc. Composite Transactions Reporting System. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The grant date present value is based on the Black-Scholes option pricing model adapted for use in calculating the fair value of executive stock options, using the following assumptions for the grants made May&nbsp;16,
2013: volatility &#150; 33.60 percent; risk free rate of return &#150; 0.79 percent; dividend yield &#150; 0.99 percent; and expected option life &#150; 5.5 years. There were no adjustments made to the model for non-transferability or risk of
forfeiture. The actual value, if any, an executive may realize will depend on the excess of the market price over the exercise price on the date the option is exercised. There is no assurance the value realized by an executive will be at or near the
value estimated by the Black-Scholes model. </TD></TR></TABLE>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_30"></A>EMPLOYMENT CONTRACTS AND TERMINATION OF </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>EMPLOYMENT AND CHANGE-IN-CONTROL ARRANGEMENTS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company has entered into certain agreements and maintains certain plans that will require the Company to provide compensation to Named Executive Officers
of the Company in the event of a termination of employment or a change in control of the Company. The amount of compensation payable to each Named Executive Officer in each situation is listed in the following table for fiscal year 2013, assuming
termination had occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2013. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:8pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt"><B>Name</B></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="2" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><B>Retirement&nbsp;or<BR>Voluntary<BR>Termination</B></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Farris serves the Company pursuant to an employment agreement, dated June&nbsp;6, 1988, under which his base salary as of year-end 2013 is $1,750,000.&nbsp;The agreement has an undefined term and may be
terminated by either the Company or Mr.&nbsp;Farris on 30 days advance written notice.&nbsp;If Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; employment is terminated without &#147;cause&#148; (as defined in the employment agreement), or if he terminates his employment
within 30 days of a reduction in his salary without a proportionate reduction in the salaries of all other Company executives, Mr.&nbsp;Farris will receive, for 36 months thereafter, (a)&nbsp;an amount equal to his base salary as it existed 60 days
prior to termination and (b)&nbsp;50 percent of the maximum amount for which he qualified under the Company&#146;s incentive compensation plan, calculated on his base compensation as it existed 60 days prior to termination. In the event of
Mr.&nbsp;Farris&#146; death during the 36-month period, the amounts described above shall be paid to his heirs or estate in addition to continuing individual dependent benefits for 60 days.&nbsp;These rights and obligations would be the same if a
termination in either of these circumstances were to follow a change of control. Mr.&nbsp;Farris has agreed not to render service to any of the Company&#146;s competitors for the term of his employment or, unless he is terminated without cause, for
36 months thereafter. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>

2011,&nbsp;January&nbsp;3, 2012, and January&nbsp;2, 2013. Upon vesting, Apache issued one share of common stock for each restricted stock unit, and 30,000 out of each 50,000 shares are not eligible for sale by Mr.&nbsp;Farris until such time as he
retires as chief executive officer or otherwise terminates employment with the Company. If Mr.&nbsp;Farris is terminated by the Company without cause and not by reason of becoming disabled or if Mr.&nbsp;Farris terminates his employment for good
reason, then the above restrictions shall lapse. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">In connection with his retirement effective March 31, 2014, Mr. Plank resigned as an officer of the Company on February 13, 2014. Also on February 13, 2014, the Company and Mr. Plank entered into a release and
settlement agreement (the &#147;Retirement Agreement&#148;) effective as of the same day. Pursuant to the terms of the Retirement Agreement, Mr. Plank will receive (i) severance pay; (ii) continued vesting of all outstanding restricted stock units
and stock options according to their original schedules and with full 10-year terms; (iii) potential cash amounts following fiscal years ending 2014 &#151; 2017 equal to the fair market value of shares under the Company&#146;s Total Shareholder
Return and 2014 Business Performance Share programs if those shares would have vested after the applicable performance period under those programs had he remained employed at the Company; and (iv) participation in the Company&#146;s retiree medical
plan with coverage costs paid by the Company through age 65. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(7)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">In addition to the foregoing, the Company has established an income continuance plan.&nbsp;The plan provides that all officers of the Company, including the Named Executive Officers, and all employees who have either
reached the age of 40, served the Company for more than ten years, or have been designated for participation based upon special skills or experience, will receive monthly payments approximating their monthly income and continued health and life
benefits from the Company for up to two years, if their employment is terminated as a result of a &#147;change in control&#148; of the Company (as defined in the plan). In this event, continued health benefit premiums would be paid so that the
after-tax income would equal what it would have if the amount of the coverage were withheld on a pre-tax basis. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(8)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Although there are no written or unwritten contracts, agreements, plans, arrangements, or obligations in place for termination without cause, the Company has, from time to time, paid executive level positions up to two
times base salary and benefits continuation for two years. Decisions by the Company to pay termination benefits, and in what amounts, are determined on an individual case basis and not as a matter of policy. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Payments Made Upon Death or Disability </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In the event of
death for Mr.&nbsp;Farris, Mr.&nbsp;Plank, Mr.&nbsp;Eichler, Mr.&nbsp;Voytovich, or Mr.&nbsp;Chambers, in addition to the benefits listed in the preceding table, payments will also be made under the Company&#146;s life insurance plan. In the event
of disability, these executive officers would benefit under the Company&#146;s disability insurance plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In connection with Mr.&nbsp;Plank&#146;s
retirement in March 2014, his life and disability insurance will both be portable upon retirement and will no longer be paid by the Company. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">68 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_31"></A>COMPENSATION COMMITTEE INTERLOCKS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>AND INSIDER PARTICIPATION </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">George D.
Lawrence, A. D. Frazier, Jr., and William C. Montgomery served on the Management Development and Compensation Committee of the Company&#146;s Board of Directors for all of 2013. John E. Lowe has served on the Management Development and Compensation
Committee since July 2013. John A. Kocur served on the Management Development and Compensation Committee until his retirement on October&nbsp;1, 2013. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mr.&nbsp;Kocur was a member of the Management Development and Compensation Committee since September 1991 and a director of the Company since 1977.
Mr.&nbsp;Kocur retired as an executive officer in 1991 and, pursuant to the terms of an employment agreement in place at the time of his retirement, he receives health, dental and vision benefits for life. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence, a member of the Management Development and Compensation Committee since May 1997, is the former president and chief executive officer of The
Phoenix Resource Companies, Inc. (&#147;Phoenix&#148;). Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence joined the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in May 1996, in conjunction with the Company&#146;s acquisition of Phoenix by a merger on May&nbsp;20, 1996, through which Phoenix
became a wholly-owned subsidiary of Apache. Pursuant to the terms of his employment agreement with Phoenix, Mr.&nbsp;Lawrence received medical and dental benefits through December 1997. Since that time, he has purchased medical and dental coverage
through the Company at full cost. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">69 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_32"></A>CERTAIN BUSINESS RELATIONSHIPS AND TRANSACTIONS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Eric J. Eichler, an employee of the Company, is the son of Rodney J. Eichler, who formerly served as Apache&#146;s president and chief operating officer and
now serves as Apache&#146;s executive advisor to the chairman and as chief executive officer, Kitimat (LNG and upstream). Eric Eichler is employed as a reservoir engineer III, a position he has held since July 2012, in Apache&#146;s Resource
Assessment group and since December 2103, in Apache Canada&#146;s reservoir and planning group. His compensation package is comparable to the employment benefits that are standard for all Apache employees. In 2013, Eric Eichler earned total
compensation of $251,389 from the Company, including base salary, annual cash incentive bonus, foreign assignment allowances, and the value of vested restricted stock units and stock options. Rodney J. Eichler does not evaluate Eric Eichler and does
not influence the amount of his compensation. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Keith L. Josey, an employee of the Company, is the brother of Scott D. Josey, who served as a member of
Apache&#146;s Board of Directors until March&nbsp;15, 2013. Keith Josey is employed as director, real estate and administrative services, a position he has held since July 2012, in Apache&#146;s General Services group. In 2013, Keith Josey earned
total compensation of $239,400 from the Company, including base salary and annual cash incentive bonus. Scott D. Josey did not influence the amount of Keith Josey&#146;s compensation. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company&#146;s Board of Directors has adopted a Code of Business Conduct, which was revised in 2013. The Code of Business Conduct prohibits conflicts of
interest between any director, officer or employee and the Company.&nbsp;The Code of Business Conduct requires directors, officers and employees to inform the Company of any transaction that involves related parties and that may give rise to a
conflict of interest.&nbsp;Pursuant to its charter, the CG&amp;N Committee reviews related party transactions on an ongoing basis to prevent conflicts of interest.&nbsp;The CG&amp;N Committee reviews a transaction in light of the affiliations of the
director, officer or employee and the affiliations of such person&#146;s immediate family.&nbsp;Transactions are presented to the CG&amp;N Committee for approval before they are entered into or, if this is not possible, for ratification after the
transaction has occurred.&nbsp;If the CG&amp;N Committee finds that a conflict of interest exists, then it will determine the appropriate remedial action, if any.&nbsp;The CG&amp;N Committee approves or ratifies a transaction if it determines that
the transaction is consistent with the best interests of the Company.&nbsp;The determination of the CG&amp;N Committee is documented in the committee&#146;s minutes.&nbsp;The Board of Directors reviews transactions to determine whether a transaction
impairs the independence of a director and such determination is documented in the Board&#146;s minutes. The Code of Business Conduct and the CG&amp;N Committee charter are available on the Company&#146;s website (www.apachecorp.com). </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">70 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="tx616560_33"></A>RATIFICATION OF APPOINTMENT OF INDEPENDENT AUDITORS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>(ITEM NO. 4 ON PROXY CARD) </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Audit
Committee has appointed Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP, an independent registered public accounting firm (the &#147;independent auditors&#148;), to audit the Company&#146;s financial statements for 2014. Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP served as the
Company&#146;s independent auditors for fiscal year 2013 and reported on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements for that year, as well as the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting.
Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP has served as the Company&#146;s independent auditors since 2002. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Representatives of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP will be present
at the annual meeting and will have an opportunity to make a statement, if they desire to do so, and to respond to appropriate questions regarding Apache&#146;s business. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Although shareholder ratification is not required, the appointment of Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP as the company&#146;s independent auditors for fiscal 2014 is
being submitted for ratification at the annual meeting because the Board believes doing so is a good corporate governance practice. Furthermore, the Audit Committee will take shareholders&#146; opinions regarding the appointment of Ernst&nbsp;&amp;
Young LLP into consideration in future deliberations. If Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP&#146;s appointment is not ratified at the annual meeting, the Audit Committee will consider the engagement of other independent accountants. The Audit Committee may
terminate Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young LLP&#146;s engagement as the Company&#146;s independent auditors without the approval of the Company&#146;s shareholders whenever the Audit Committee deems appropriate. </P>

performed by the independent auditor. Audit-related services include, among other things, due diligence services pertaining to potential business acquisitions/dispositions; accounting consultations related to accounting, financial reporting or
disclosure matters not classified as &#147;audit services&#148;, assistance with understanding and implementing new accounting and financial reporting guidance from rulemaking authorities; financial audits of employee benefit plans; agreed upon or
expanded audit procedures related to accounting and/or billing records required to respond to or comply with financial, accounting or regulatory reporting matters; and assistance with internal controls, reporting requirements. </TD></TR></TABLE>
